    <div id="artwork-details">
    <div id="tombstone">

    <p>    Pavel Petrovich Sokolov-Skalia<br />
(Born Strel'nia, 1899; died Moscow, 1961)<br />
Aleksandr Alekseevich Zharov<br />
(Born Semenovskaia, 1904; died Moscow, 1984)<br />
    </p>
    <h3><em>Four Lessons</em>, TASS No. 1305, October 2, 1945</h3>

    <p>
    Stencil<br />    1350 x 1222 mm<br />    [1]<br />
The blood-thirsty Japanese bandit got greedy<br />
And developed an appetite for foreign lands.<br />
In our coastal region in 1920<br />
He attacked us to his own detriment.<br />
<br />
[2]<br />
The Samurai didn’t forget the lesson.<br />
At Khasan he cried out “Bonsai.”<br />
The indefatigable Japanese bandit<br />
Was also beaten there, as we know.<br />
<br />
Inscription on map:<br />
Khasan<br />
<br />
[3]<br />
Soon his impudence brought him to Khalkhin-Gol River.<br />
Again he attacked, having gained in confidence.<br />
But in vain at Khalkhin-Gol did he wet his feet :<br />
Again the samurai was hit across the teeth.<br />
<br />
Inscription on map:<br />
Khalkhin-Gol<br />
<br />
[4] <br />
The Samurai is being given a final lesson<br />
So that he might never rise again.<br />
Finally peace has been established<br />
By our powerful hand in the Far East.<br />    Ne boltai! Collection, Obj: 206082</p>
        
        <!--<p id="dept-gallery">--><!--<br />-->
         <!--</p>-->
    </p>
    </div><!--/tombstone-->

